<br>
----------<br>
&quot;Do you give someone a gift on their birthday and then a few months later stop being friends and ask for that gift back? I don't think so.&quot;<br>
----------<br>
<br>
That's your analogy, which holds true &quot;depending on the guild&quot;.  But it can't be applied as an example for *all* guilds.<br>
<br>
----------<br>
When your business gives you a faster computer on your desk so that you can do your job more efficiently, what would they say if you took it home with you upon just quiting or being layed off?<br>
----------<br>
<br>
That's another way of looking at it.<br>
<br>
Some guilds are run the way your analogy is written, some run the other way.  You know what you're getting into by reading the guild's policy.<br>
<br>
The problem comes when someone who believes in your analogy joins a guild who's leader and other members believe in the second analogy I just made.<br>
<br>
Everyone plays this game their own way.  No one can be forced to play it someone elses way... but in the case of a guild, compremises are made.  Obviously, as in any orginization, they have rules which you must follow else they won't let you be a member and join them.  If the rules were stated up front (would be dumb to join a guild without knowing their loot policies), by joining that guild you've agreed to their loot policy and agree to abide by it.  If you didn't agree to it, you obviously wouldn't be in said guild as they're not going to invite someone that says they won't follow their rules.  If you hide it from your guildies that you don't agree with their policy, then choose to go against it by keeping something that was understood to belong to the guild, that is theft.<br>
<br>
